<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Actually Makes a Variety “Fast” in Practice</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Shorter maturity time.</strong> Fewer days to harvest gives more flexibility in planting.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Reliable development.</strong> Some varieties reach maturity more consistently under variable conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Better fit for your climate.</strong> Heat, light, and season length all affect how quickly a crop grows.
  </p>

  <p>
    A variety that is fast on paper may not be fast in your garden if those factors do not line up.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Fast Varieties Matter More Than People Expect</h2>

  <p>
    Faster crops do more than just finish earlier.
  </p>

  <p>
    They allow you to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>fit additional plantings into the same space</li>
    <li>reduce the risk of crops failing to finish</li>
    <li>recover more easily from delayed planting</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This becomes especially important later in the season, when timing margins are tighter.
  </p>

  <p>
    Knowing whether a crop will actually finish in time — and understanding <a href="/guides/will-my-crop-mature-before-first-frost/">how maturity aligns with your first frost</a> — helps turn fast varieties into real results.
  </p>
</section>

